Tom,<br>
   We have a fairly sizable Hmong community in Philadelphia. My parish has Masses in the Hmong language.  Have heard Scirpture read and hymns sung in it at the Mass celebrating the parish feast day.  I find the singing quite beautiful.<br><br>
   What I think of our conduct in Laos is probably unprintable.  I recently read of an elderly Homng farmer in my home state of Wisconsin that committed suicide, so he wouldn't be a burden to his family, after he read of the new law putting restrictions on benefits to legal immigrants.<br><br>
   Americans are very rarely consciously cruel, but we can be as self-centered and thoughtless at times as anyone on the planet.  More than anybody, this country is responsible for the Hmong being forcibly dragged culturally from about the 10th to the 20th century.  As a people it was like insisting that they cross the Grand Canyon on a high wire without a net.  The results haven't been pretty much of the time.  Figuratively speaking, when the Hmong and Montagnards asked for the promised life savers, we asked if they wanted a breath mint.<br><br>
P.S. If Betty is watching and reading out there, please contact me. 
